A few comments to mention before conducting this analysis:

  • The data collected has been separated into mens and womens categories, this is in no way meant to dismiss trans women in this industry, it is simply how government agencies have separated the data.

  • It is also understood that is it not required to have gotten a degree (technology related or not) to be able to work in the technology field. For the sake of drawing conclusions I am using data on women who have gotten computer science degrees in the United States.

Tranforming data into a time series

men_pct_ts =ts((working_data[,6]), start = c(2012,1), end = c(2022,12), frequency = 12)
wmn_pct_ts = ts((working_data[,5]), start = c(2012,1), end = c(2022,12), frequency = 12)
bac_wmn = ts((degree_data[,4]), start = c(2011), end = c(2020,1), frequency = 1)
bac_men = ts((degree_data[,3]), start = c(2011), end = c(2020,1), frequency = 1)
bac_wmn_pct = ts((degree_data[,5]), start = c(2011), end = c(2020,1), frequency = 1)

masters_wmn = ts((degree_data[,8]), start = c(2011), end = c(2020,1), frequency = 1)
masters_men = ts((degree_data[,7]), start = c(2011), end = c(2020,1), frequency = 1)
masters_wmn_pct = ts((degree_data[,9]), start = c(2011), end = c(2020,1), frequency = 1)

doctorate_wmn = ts((degree_data[,13]), start = c(2011), end = c(2020,1), frequency = 1)
doctorate_men = ts((degree_data[,12]), start = c(2011), end = c(2020,1), frequency = 1)
doctorate_wmn_pct = ts((degree_data[,14]), start = c(2011), end = c(2020,1), frequency = 1)

Now I will plot the percentages of Bachelors, Masters, and Doctorate Computer Science degrees awarded to women.

ts.plot((cbind(bac_wmn_pct,masters_wmn_pct, doctorate_wmn_pct)), gpars = list(col = c("deepskyblue4", "sienna2", "orchid3")))

The plot above shows that Masters programs (orange) has the highest percentage of degrees awarded to women, Bachelors programs (blue) have the lowest percentage of degrees awarded to women, and Doctorate programs (purple) are in the middle.

Lets look into the montly data for women holding positions in technology.

boxplot(wmn_pct_ts~cycle(wmn_pct_ts), xlab = "Month", ylab = "Percentage")

We can see from the boxplot above that the mean stays consistent throughout the year. We do see outliers from the months March to August.

The following graph shows the monthly percentage of women working in technology (NAICS code : 42343) from January 2012 to January 2022.

plot(wmn_pct_ts)

From the graph above, we can see some interesting peaks and troughs in this data set. In 2017, there is a sharp drop from 30% to roughly 27%. From 2017 we see an upward trend in the data until a peak is hit in late 2019 of roughly 33.5%

Once I collect more data, I will be curious to see any trends in 2017 and 2019 that could account for the spikes we see in the graph above.

Decomposing

As we have monthly data for the women working in technology dataset, it would be worthwhile to decompose the model to look for seasonal trends

wmnpct_decomp = decompose(wmn_pct_ts)

plot(wmnpct_decomp)

We can see from the decomposed plot that the mean is changing over time, which points to non-stationarity. It would be helpful here to conduct an ADF Test to obtain a p-value for our model.

adf.test(wmn_pct_ts)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  wmn_pct_ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -2.2999, Lag order = 5, p-value = 0.4518
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

The p-value here is 0.4518, which means we fail to reject the null at the Alpha Significance Level of 5%. With the ADF Test and the visual from the decomposed plot, I think it is safe to say the model is non-stationary.

Differencing and Log Transformations

To help solve this case on non-stationarity, I am beginning to difference the model by using the diff function.

wmn_pct_diff = diff(wmn_pct_ts)

plot(wmn_pct_diff)

By plotting this differenced model, we can see that the mean is now steady across time. The variance is not showing an issue here, therefore it would not be beneficial to continue to the log transformation steps to change the stationarity of this model. To be sure it would be good to check the ADF and ACF Tests.

adf.test(wmn_pct_diff)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  wmn_pct_diff
## Dickey-Fuller = -3.2049, Lag order = 5, p-value = 0.09018
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

The ADF Test here still gives us a p-value above the Alpha Significance Level, which would mean we fail to reject the null and that the data is non-stationary. One thing to note is that the p-value did decrease roughly .3 after creating a differenced model. It would be best to conduct an ACF Test as well.

acf(wmn_pct_diff)

The Autocorrelation Function Plot above shows highly indicates stationarity as our values stay within the designated range of -.2 and .2.
